    "1643623889c6d0c699": {
      "type": "accordion",
      "blocks": {
        "164362388910ff9bcb-0": {
          "type": "text",
          "settings": {
            "heading": "Where do you ship?",
            "description": "<p>Since “Company name” is still growing, we're currently only able to ship within the continental United States. (Sorry Alaska and Hawaii!) Because our wet food is shipped with enough dry ice to last for just 2-3 days, it would be hard for us to guarantee freshness outside of this area-- for now.</p>"
          }
        },
        "164362388910ff9bcb-1": {
          "type": "text",
          "settings": {
            "heading": "Is your packaging recyclable?",
            "description": "<p>We're proud to say that all of our packaging is 100% recyclable. The insulators we use to keep everything nice and cold are actually made of a corn-based styrofoam that is completely biodegradable. In fact, you can wash it right down your sink! Simply remove the insulators from their green plastic bags and place them in the sink-- we recommend just one or two pieces at a time. Turn the water on and watch the foam melt away!<br/><br/>The green bags that held the insulators can go out, along with all the cardboard, to your regular recycling receptacle. </p>"
          }
        },
        "164362388910ff9bcb-2": {
          "type": "text",
          "settings": {
            "heading": "I opened my package and the dry ice is all gone! Is the food still safe to serve?",
            "description": "<p>One of the more fun features of dry ice is how it sublimates (i.e., it goes straight from being frozen solid to a gas, without \"melting\" or turning into a liquid.) That said, if you open your box and there's no dry ice left, it's not the end of the world. As long as the packets of wet food are either still frozen or at a temperature of 40ºF or lower, they're perfectly safe to refreeze and serve as normal.</p>"
          }
        }
      },
